ss/ipc`, `yieldless/node`, and `yieldless/env`"},"246":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#install","content":"TypeScript 5.5+ is the target baseline. The package is compiled with `isolatedDeclarations` enabled."},"247":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"`safeTry()` and `safeTrySync()` let you treat common failures as data instead of exception control flow."},"248":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"That pattern is the center of the library. Every module is designed to fit back into the same `[error, value]` shape."},"249":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"When a tuple flow grows past one branch, use `yieldless/result` to keep it readable."},"250":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-1-stop-throwing-for-routine-failures","content":"Keep this modest. If one `if (error)` branch is clearer, use the branch."},"251":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"`runTaskGroup()` gives you a shared abort signal and sibling failure propagation."},"252":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"If `readRefs()` throws, the group aborts the shared signal, waits for `readStatus()` to settle, and then rethrows the original failure.\nIf the request or UI flow already has an `AbortSignal`, pass it in so the whole group inherits upstream cancellation."},"253":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"When the work is a list rather than a few named tasks, use `mapLimit()` to keep pressure on the outside world under control."},"254":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"The result order matches the input order, and the first tuple error aborts the remaining in-flight work."},"255":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-2-group-related-work-under-one-cancellation-signal","content":"For async streams or generators, reach for `yieldless/iterable` instead of materializing everything first."},"256":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"Retries should stay close to transport boundaries: HTTP, queues, database connections, and subprocesses that can legitimately fail for transient reasons."},"257":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-3-add-retries-where-the-outside-world-is-unreliable","content":"The retry loop respects `AbortSignal`, so if a parent task group is canceled, the pending backoff timer is canceled too."},"258":{"id":"/docs/guides/quickstart-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/quickstart#step-4-keep-the-edges-boring","content":"When a boundary needs a f