Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client"},"290":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"An end-to-end shape for a desktop Git app using IPC tuples, abortable subprocesses, and typed renderer calls."},"291":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"292":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"293":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"294":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#renderer-usage","content":"Renderer usage"},"295":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Why this boundary feels cleaner"},"296":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"297":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"298":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","content":"Yieldless fits Electron well because the important boundaries in an Electron app are all failure-heavy: the renderer asks for work through IPC, the main process touches the filesystem, the main process launches long-running child processes like `git clone`."},"299":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#main-process-implementation","content":"If the window is torn down or a parent task group is canceled, the subprocess is aborted through Node's native child-process signal handling."},"300":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The renderer never depends on Electron's lossy thrown-error conversion."},"301":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"The main process can use the same tuple style it uses everywhere else."},"302":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#why-this-boundary-feels-cleaner","content":"Long-running Git subprocesses can be canceled as soon as the UI no longer cares about them."},"303":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate status reads if several panels can request the same repository at once."},"304":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#good-additions","content":"Wait for one app or window event with cleanup."},"305":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Do not expose arbitrary IPC channels to the renderer."},"306":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-git-client#avoid","content":"Build a small preload bridge with `createIpcBridge()` or `createAbortableIpcBridge()` so the renderer only sees the operations it is allowed to call."},"307":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"page","content":"Electron PR Review Workbench","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench"},"308":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"A practical architecture for a GitHub pull-request review desktop app using tuples in the right places and ordinary UI state in the renderer."},"309":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-contract","content":"Main-process contract"},"310":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"Main-process implementation"},"311":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#preload-bridge","content":"Preload bridge"},"312":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"Renderer state"},"313":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Why this fits PR review tools well"},"314":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Good additions"},"315":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"316":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Rule of thumb"},"317":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"If you are building a GitHub PR review app in Electron, Yieldless fits best in the main process, preload bridge, and service layer. It is less useful as the shape of your React component state."},"318":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"That distinction matters:"},"319":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Use tuples while you are still doing failure-heavy work: GitHub API calls, local Git reads, diff parsing, cache reads, IPC boundaries."},"320":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","content":"Once the renderer receives the result, fold it into ordinary screen state and move on."},"321":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"The important thing here is not the exact helper list. It is the layering:"},"322":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/error` keeps the boundary readable with `ok()` and `err()`."},"323":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/all` loads the PR payload in parallel."},"324":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/task` gives the whole request one shared cancellation signal."},"325":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#main-process-implementation","content":"`yieldless/node` keeps Git subprocess failures in the same tuple contract."},"326":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"This is the point where Yieldless should usually stop being the dominant shape."},"327":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#renderer-state","content":"That keeps the renderer normal. Components render `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, or `error`. They do not need to carry `[error, value]` through every prop."},"328":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Pull-request work crosses many noisy boundaries: GitHub HTTP, local Git, caches, and Electron IPC."},"329":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"Cancellation matters because users jump between PRs quickly and the old load should stop being important."},"330":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#why-this-fits-pr-review-tools-well","content":"The renderer wants stable view state, not a low-level transport shape."},"331":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-23","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Deduplicate duplicate PR loads while a user is switching tabs or refreshing panels."},"332":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-24","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#good-additions","content":"Use bounded iterable work when processing many files in a diff."},"333":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-25","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Do not keep tuples as your component model."},"334":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-26","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#avoid","content":"Fold the tuple once into `idle`, `loading`, `ready`, and `error` state. UI code should speak in screen states."},"335":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-27","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Use Yieldless in the main process and preload boundary."},"336":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-28","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Convert tuples into domain state at the renderer edge."},"337":{"id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench-29","page_id":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/electron-pr-review-workbench#rule-of-thumb","content":"Do not force tuple results deep into component trees."},"338":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"page","content":"Resilient Service Flow","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Recipes","Recipes"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow"},"339":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-0","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"A practical backend flow that combines tuples, retries, validation, routing, and cancellation."},"340":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-1","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"The moving parts"},"341":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-2","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#route-handler","content":"Route handler"},"342":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-3","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Why this holds up well in production"},"343":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-4","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"Good variation: add a remote dependency"},"344":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-5","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"Avoid: retrying the whole handler"},"345":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-6","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Rules worth keeping"},"346":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-7","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","content":"This recipe shows the shape Yieldless is best at: an HTTP request that validates input, performs a few pieces of I/O, retries the flaky part, and returns a normal JSON response."},"347":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-8","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/schema` validates input without throwing"},"348":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-9","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/fetch` keeps HTTP calls in tuple form"},"349":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-10","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/retry` handles transient I/O noise"},"350":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-11","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/task` keeps sibling work under one cancellation signal"},"351":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-12","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#the-moving-parts","content":"`yieldless/router` turns tuple results into a plain response"},"352":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-13","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Validation failures never take the exception path."},"353":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-14","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"If `loadRefs()` fails, `loadStatus()` is aborted immediately."},"354":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-15","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"Retry timers are cancellable because they run through `AbortSignal`."},"355":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-16","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#why-this-holds-up-well-in-production","content":"The handler body stays linear. There is no framework-specific DSL to learn."},"356":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-17","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#good-variation-add-a-remote-dependency","content":"The retry policy is attached to the flaky network call, not to the whole request."},"357":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-18","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#avoid-retrying-the-whole-handler","content":"That repeats validation, routing decisions, and any side effects. Retry the noisy boundary instead."},"358":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-19","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Validate early and return early."},"359":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-20","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Retry only the noisy boundary, not the entire request."},"360":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-21","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Spawn sibling work only when both tasks should die together."},"361":{"id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow-22","page_id":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/recipes/resilient-service-flow#rules-worth-keeping","content":"Map domain misses to explicit HTTP errors like `NotFoundError`."},"362":{"id":"/docs/reference/all","page_id":"/docs/ref