"381":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"If any task or mapped item returns `[error, null]`, siblings are aborted before the final tuple is returned."},"382":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"`race()` aborts losing tasks immediately, then waits for them to settle before it returns."},"383":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#behavior-notes","content":"Thrown task and mapper failures are normalized into tuple failures internally."},"384":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#when-to-prefer-runtaskgroup-instead","content":"Use `all()`, `race()`, and `mapLimit()` when the work is already tuple-native. Use `runTaskGroup()` when you want imperative fan-out and regular promise values."},"385":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `all()` for a small, fixed set of independent tuple tasks."},"386":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-23","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `mapLimit()` when a list could be large or expensive."},"387":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-24","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#good","content":"Use `race()` when the first success or first failure should settle the operation."},"388":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-25","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not pass work that ignores the signal and expect cancellation to be immediate."},"389":{"id":"/docs/reference/all-26","page_id":"/docs/reference/all","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/all#avoid","content":"Do not use `all()` for thousands of items. Use `mapLimit()` or `yieldless/iterable` so you can control pressure."},"390":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"page","content":"yieldless/batcher","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher"},"391":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"DataLoader-style keyed batching for tuple-returning async reads."},"392":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"Exports"},"393":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#example","content":"Example"},"394":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"Behavior notes"},"395":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#good","content":"Good"},"396":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/batcher#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"397":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"`yieldless/batcher` coalesces nearby `load(key)` calls into one `loadMany(keys, signal)` call. It is useful when many screens, resolvers, or workflow steps can ask for related data in the same tick."},"398":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher","content":"The module stays intentionally boring: it does not cache, it does not add a scheduler, and it does not require a runtime. It batches pending keys, maps results back by index, and returns tuple results to each caller."},"399":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`createBatcher({ loadMany, waitMs, maxBatchSize }): Batcher`"},"400":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`class MissingBatchResultError extends Error`"},"401":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`type Batcher<Key, Value, E> = { load, clear, pending }`"},"402":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#exports","content":"`type BatcherLoadOptions = { signal?: AbortSignal }`"},"403":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`waitMs` defaults to `0`, which batches calls queued in the same turn."},"404":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`maxBatchSize` flushes a batch early when enough keys are waiting."},"405":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`loadMany()` must return values in the same order as the input keys."},"406":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"If `loadMany()` returns `[error, null]`, every waiting caller receives that error."},"407":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"If a result is missing for an index, that caller receives `MissingBatchResultError`."},"408":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"A pending `load()` can be aborted before the batch flushes."},"409":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#behavior-notes","content":"`clear(reason)` resolves all pending loads with the reason."},"410":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#good","content":"Use a batcher where the backend already supports bulk reads."},"411":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-20","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#good","content":"Keep caching separate when you need both."},"412":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-21","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#avoid","content":"Do not use batching to hide write side effects."},"413":{"id":"/docs/reference/batcher-22","page_id":"/docs/reference/batcher","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/batcher#avoid","content":"Prefer explicit write orchestration for mutations, and use `yieldless/batcher` for read-like keyed loading."},"414":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"page","content":"yieldless/breaker","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Reference","Reference"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker"},"415":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-0","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker","content":"Circuit breakers for flaky tuple-returning dependencies."},"416":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-1","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"Exports"},"417":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-2","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker#example","content":"Example"},"418":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-3","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"Behavior notes"},"419":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-4","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker#good","content":"Good"},"420":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-5","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/reference/breaker#avoid","content":"Avoid"},"421":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-6","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker","content":"`yieldless/breaker` protects a dependency after repeated failures. It tracks a small state machine: `closed`, `open`, and `half-open`. When enough failures trip the breaker, new calls fail fast with `CircuitOpenError` until the cooldown passes."},"422":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-7","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker","content":"Use it around external services, subprocess-heavy integrations, or any expensive boundary where repeated failures should stop causing more pressure."},"423":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-8","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"`createCircuitBreaker(operation, options): CircuitBreaker`"},"424":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-9","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"`class CircuitOpenError extends Error`"},"425":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-10","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"`type CircuitBreakerState = \"closed\" | \"half-open\" | \"open\"`"},"426":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-11","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"`type CircuitBreakerOptions = { failureThreshold, cooldownMs, successThreshold, shouldTrip, onStateChange }`"},"427":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-12","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#exports","content":"`type CircuitBreaker = callable & { state, failureCount, reset }`"},"428":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-13","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"The breaker opens after `failureThreshold` tripping failures."},"429":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-14","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"While open, calls return `[new CircuitOpenError(), null]`."},"430":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-15","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"After `cooldownMs`, the next call moves the breaker to `half-open`."},"431":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-16","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"A half-open success closes the breaker once `successThreshold` is reached."},"432":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-17","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"A half-open failure opens it again."},"433":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-18","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"`shouldTrip(error)` lets you ignore expected failures such as validation errors."},"434":{"id":"/docs/reference/breaker-19","page_id":"/docs/reference/breaker","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/reference/breaker#behavior-notes","content":"`reset()` closes the breaker and clears counts."},